      <hedline>
        <hl1>Ideas, Not Personalities</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Brent Muirhead letter holds that presidential campaign has been plagued by absence of serious debate over issues</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''The Tyranny of the Undecided Voter,'' by Alan Wolfe (Op-Ed, Oct. 22):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''The Tyranny of the Undecided Voter,'' by Alan Wolfe (Op-Ed, Oct. 22):</p>
        <p>Today's presidential campaigns struggle with capturing our attention because people have grown cynical about the government. Americans have real questions about politicians who have a tendency to promise too much to win their votes.</p>
        <p>Television coverage of Al Gore and George W. Bush has been quite superficial by stressing the candidates' clothing or facial expressions. Yet, undecided voters are guilty of not formulating a political philosophy to help them evaluate the candidates.</p>
        <p>Perhaps it is time to evaluate our election process, which is plagued by the absence of serious debate over ideas. The excessive emphasis on personality fails to address the importance of supporting a party platform that transcends individual politicians. Ultimately, our nation needs a president who has the integrity and vision to use his power to serve our vital national and international interests.</p>
        <p>BRENT MUIRHEAD  Alpharetta, Ga., Oct. 22, 2000</p>
      </block>
